{
  "doc_id": "20055",
  "text": "A number of turn-design features have constructed the teacher's turns as disagreement-implicative but at the same time as a facilitator for more extended learner turns in our study. First, the employment of a temporal delay has been observed, which demonstrably creates a break in interaction [CITATION_1] . Second, hedging and delaying devices are deployed which delay the production of the actual response. Last, the locally contingent ways in which the teacher manages her body seems to be critical for the students to overview the adequacy of their prior responses. In other words, students orient to all these interactional resources employed by the teacher by attempting to produce increments over their just-prior contribution.",
